Exploratory Analysis -#Numerical summaries

  1. Mean (0.06918883): On average, across all states, the COVID case count per population is approximately 6.9, meaning there are around 0.069 cases per person in the population.

  2. Median (0.07229155): The median, which represents the middle value of the dataset, is slightly higher than the mean. This suggests that the distribution of COVID case counts per population might be slightly right-skewed, with some states having higher case counts than others.

  3. Standard Deviation (0.02237431): The standard deviation indicates the spread or variability of the COVID case counts per population around the mean. With a standard deviation of approximately 0.022, we can infer that the case counts vary by about 0.022 from the mean. This suggests that while the average case count is around 0.069, individual states may have case counts that deviate from this average by up to approximately 0.022.

Model 0

  • Analyze the model’s performance and summarize your findings.

    For Linear Regression model with 1 predictor:Interpretation:

    • The intercept term is significant (p < 0.001), indicating that it is significantly different from zero.

    • The coefficient for Median_Household_Income_2020 is negative and statistically significant (p = 0.0499), indicating a significant relationship between median household income and COVID-19 case count per population. Specifically, the coefficient estimate for Median_Household_Income_2020 is approximately -5.715e-07. This suggests that for every one unit increase in median household income, the COVID-19 case count per population decreases by approximately 5.715e-07 units, holding other variables constant.

    • The model explains a small proportion of the variance in the response variable (covid_case_count_per_pop), with a multiple R-squared of 0.07937.

    • The F-statistic indicates that the overall model is statistically significant at the 0.05 level (p = 0.04987).

    • Overall, the model suggests that there is a weak negative relationship between the median household income in 2020 and the COVID-19 case count per population. The model suggests that median household income is associated with COVID-19 case count per population, but it explains only a small portion of the variability in the response variable.ndefined

Model 1

  • Here is the model summary: - Coefficients: Each coefficient represents the estimated change in the response variable (COVID-19 case count per population) for a one-unit change in the predictor variable, holding other variables constant.

    • Intercept: The intercept represents the estimated COVID-19 case count per population when all predictor variables are zero.

K-Nearest Neighbors

Model 1

  • Analyze the model’s performance and summarize your findings.

    Here is the model summary:

    1. RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error): This metric measures the average deviation of the predicted values from the actual values. A lower RMSE indicates better model performance. In your case, the RMSE is approximately 0.022, suggesting that, on average, the predicted COVID-19 case count per population deviates from the actual count by around 0.022 units.

    2. R-squared (Coefficient of Determination): This metric indicates the proportion of the variance in the target variable that is explained by the model. It ranges from 0 to 1, with higher values indicating a better fit. In your case, the R-squared value is approximately 0.016, which means that only about 1.6% of the variance in the COVID-19 case count per population is explained by the model.

    3. MAE (Mean Absolute Error): This metric measures the average absolute difference between the predicted and actual values. Similar to RMSE, a lower MAE indicates better model performance. Your MAE is approximately 0.016, implying that, on average, the predicted COVID-19 case count per population deviates from the actual count by around 0.016 units.

    Overall, based on these metrics, the KNN model seems to have limited predictive performance, as indicated by the relatively high RMSE and MAE values and the low R-squared value. This suggests that the model may not be capturing the underlying patterns in the data effectively or that the chosen features may not be strong predictors of the COVID-19 case count per population.
